out love’, probably in the sense ‘fancy free’.","some early examples, such as Richard Lovelas (Kent 1344), may have as their second element Middle English <i>las(se)</i> ‘girl’, ‘maiden’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Lovelace was born in 1247, in England, United Kingdom, his father, John (William) Lovelace/Luvlaz, was 22 and his mother, Mrs John William Luvlaz, was 23. He had at least 1 son with Mrs William Lovelace. He died about 1270, in his hometown, at the age of 24."},"et":{"1247–about 1270":"1247–umbes 1270","1247–1270":"1247–1270","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1270–1300":"1270–1300","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1225–Female":"1225–Surnud","1247":"1247","about 1270":"umbes 1270","1225":"1225","1300":"1300","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fi":{"1247–about 1270":"1247–noin 1270","1247–1270":"1247–1270","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","1270–1300":"1270–1300","1225–Male":"1225–Kuollut","1225–Female":"1225–Kuollut","1247":"1247","about 1270":"noin 1270","1225":"1225","1300":"1300","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fr":{"1247–about 1270":"1247–environ 1270","1247–1270":"1